4 The /etc/os-release Resets when base-files updates. to prevent that, you can mark base-files as held sudo apt-mark hold base-files
5 Run sudo apt install links
  then links https://github.com/Haikal02-alt/Syslack-Linux Then find Screenshot from 2026-01-31 16-31-30
  then Save the Screenshot from 2026-01-31 16-31-30 If You See 543212867-3fb3c0d3-784e-46f0-b862-6fd822089d3e.png Change To syslack-logo.png
  then run sudo mv /home/yourusername/syslack-logo.png /usr/share/pixmaps
6 Then sudo nano /etc/os-release and add LOGO=/usr/share/pixmaps/syslack-logo.png
7 run sudo nano /etc/default/grub then Change GRUB_TIMEOUT=2 To GRUB_TIMEOUT=5
  Then change GRUB_DISTRIBUTOR='lsb_release -i -s 2> /dev/null || echo Debian' To GRUB_DISTRIBUTOR="Syslack Linux"
  Then sudo update-grub
8 You May Stop The Services Of Snap
   sudo systemctl stop snapd
   sudo systemctl disable snapd

  Purge Snapd (Recommended)
  sudo apt purge snapd

  Clean Up Leftover Directories
  rm -rf ~/snap
  sudo rm -rf /var/snap /var/lib/snapd /var/cache/snapd

  Autoremove
  sudo apt autoremove

  System Updates: Ubuntu may reinstall Snapd during major upgrades. To prevent this, you can block Snapd from being reinstalled:
  sudo apt-mark hold snapd

9 Change Some Ubuntu To Syslack On /etc/issue on sudo nano /etc/issue If You See Ubuntu 16.04 LTS \n \1 Change it To Syslack Linux \n \1
  Also run sudo nano /etc/issue.net Then Change Ubuntu 16.04 LTS To Syslack Linux

10 Remove /etc/update-motd.d with sudo rm -rf /etc/update-motd.d

11 links https://github.com/syslacklinux/Syslack-Linux-Archive/blob/main/starfield.png
   then click starfield.png then save
   then run sudo mv /home/yourusername/starfield.png /usr/share/pixmaps
   then run sudo nano /etc/default/grub
   then add GRUB_BACKGROUND="/usr/share/pixmaps/starfield.png"
   then sudo update-grub

12 Install memtest86+ (If you are using Legacy BIOS 32 Bit Hardware) sudo apt install memtest86+ -y

